,Recommended,431710,24384190,"Posted: 17 July, 2016",all,stardustsunday,"A fun, bite-sized 1-hour gemThe Space Pilgrim saga continues. As with the 1st episode, this one is self-contained, meaning that you don't have to play the episodes before or after to enjoy the gaming experience. But it certainly helps if you've completed Episode I first, as some elements of the story in this episode refer back to it.The Good- Ambience, setting, sound, immersion- Play as 2 different characters- More adventure game obstacles to solve compared to Episode I- Some puzzles were not bad- Fun achievements- Story, pacing and narration keep you interested- A good number of objects & environments to interact with & explore- Slightly longer in length compared to Episode IThe Bad- Having to go through the same tedious 3-step process each time with the airlock is a pain and time-waster- Flawed grammar in a few areasConclusionFun to play no doubt, but much like Episode I, is quite short. Worth a buy when on sale. The story continues in Episode III, but Episode II does have a proper ending so you can always stop after this game."
,Recommended,431710,26309058,"Posted: 30 October, 2016",all,Royal Rambler,"This is the second installment of the Space Pilgrim adventure.It occurs a year after the first chapter.Some changes have obviously taken place seeing how quite a bit of time has passed.Some of the characters' past interactions have lead to the blooming of a friendship, and this is depicted in this second chapter of the SP saga.One of the passengers from back then grew closer to protagonist Gail Pilgrim (the pilot of starship 'Quicksilver' - where most of the scenarios take place in the former chapter).This friendship blossomed to such an extent that the former passenger now co-manages the starship with Gail. The character in question is also intermittently playable (which allows for a bit of variation & excitement). Meaning, the player is handed control over Gail first & then her friend when the story calls for it.In this chapter there is yet another handful of passengers on board (and some of these turn out to be allies, and others turn out to be antagonists), as was the case in SP1.The starship serves as both a passenger & cargo ship (meaning it transports people but also goods). And there's more of an emphasis on the latter in chapter II.And just like chapter I, the game is divided into 3 main acts, which each focus on a specific issue.The story now contains elements of one (playable) flashback (which is totally awesome and revolves around a trained individual who was meant to serve as a soldier, but somehow ended up as a fugitive).How this happened is explained & depicted as you play.It's interesting to note that the starship still looks the same as before and this chapter feels like a plausible sequel to the former (meaning the story makes sense and does unfold logically).The dialogue system has been expanded as well (i.e. more questions to ask).And I appreciate that very much :).NB: this game contains some brash language & risqué jokes at times (you've been warned!)Trivia:In the former chapter, there was mention of a particular organization (the J.A.C.) which was only named by it's abbreviated form.In the second chapter the role of said organization is clarified (i.e. full name is revealed) and further expounded, to such an extent where the subject becomes of great interest to the crew (and story in general)."
76561198132503739,Recommended,431710,24198227,"Posted: 8 July, 2016",all,aquatorrent,"My playtime: 01:34:04 (based on internal clock)IntroSpace Pilgrim Episode II: Epsilon Indi is an adventure game about fugitives who disguised themselves as a passanger in a spaceship and the ones who chase them. Like the first episode (if you played it before), this game will mostly made you to interact with objects and read the story.GraphicsThe sprites used are almost the same with the first episode with a few addition for other map with a different UI color. As i mentioned in the first episode review, the sprites and UI are used beautifully.MusicThe music describe the outer space perfectly, with its almost-nothing sound. The SFX is also used appropriately.StoryThis game happens around one year after the first episode. Unlike the title name, this episode has a standalone story from the first one, although there are some references. Like the first episode, this story is very short and well thought. Unlike the first episode, this episode ending doesn't wrap the story; there are some room for questions and mysteries for episode 3 and the story will be continued in that episode.The gameAs i said before, you'll mostly interact with objects and read the story. Although you might stuck at some point, all you have to do is just press your action button on all things you can find in order to advance through the story.I just replayed the game with mouse control and i realized that the mouse control isn't very comfortable to use (unless you are really lazy to play the game with both hands, that is). You'll need to be careful when you want to combine items, there is no button to bring the menu screen, and the autopath tend to screw you up when you are going to the kitchen and lavatory.Pros:- Short and well thought storyCons:- No dash button- Mouse control isn't optimized yet (it's hard to combine items, there is no ""menu button"", and the autopath tend to stuck when you are going to kitchen and lavatory)ConclusionThis is a short RPG Maker game about fugitives who disguised themselves as a passanger in a spaceship and the one who chases them.Should you buy this game?Yes.If you love to buy RPG Maker game, this one is a must. If you love the first episode, you better buy this game. However, if you are the type who think twice before buying RPG Maker game, because of its length, you might want to skip it or buy it when it's on sale."
